M|Tabl|tx|---
M|Comp|- **|** B2B SaaS (project management software)
M|Comp|- **|** $3.2M ARR
M|Comp|- **|** 35
M|Comp|- **|** 4 years prior
M|Comp|- **|** ce (Visionary), co (Integrator), VP Sales, VP Engineering, VP mk
M|Star|it|rv growth had stalled at 15% year-over-year after three years of 80%+ growth
M|Star|it|The ce was involved in every decision, creating a bottleneck
M|Star|it|Engineering and Sales were in constant conflict over roadmap priorities
M|Star|it|No formal meeting rhythm; ad hoc meetings consumed 30+ hours per week across leadership
M|Star|it|Three key engineers quit in six months, citing lack of direction
M|EOS |**Qu|** Focus Day established the Accountability Chart. The ce stepped into the Visionary role and the co formally became the Integrator. Weekly Level 10 meetings replaced all ad hoc leadership meetings. Five quarterly rocks were set, inc hiring a VP of cs sc.
M|EOS |**Qu|** V/TO done. Core Values defined: "Ship It," "cs Obsessed," "Radical Candor." Core Focus: "Make teams productive" + "Project management for mid-mk SaaS." A weekly Scorecard w/ 10 metrics was launched.
M|EOS |**Qu|** People Analyzer run on all 35 employees. Four people were identified as wrong person/wrong seat. Two were moved to better-fitting roles. Two exited. The engineering-sales conflict was IDS'd: root cause was no pd prioritization process. A core process ("The Roadmap Engine") was documented.
M|EOS |**Qu|** Department-level Level 10 meetings rolled out. Department scorecards created. Rock completion rate hit 85%.
M|Resu|tx|\| Metric \| Before EOS \| After 12 Months \| After 24 Months \|
M|Resu|tx|\|--------\|-----------\|-----------------\|-----------------\|
M|Resu|tx|\| ARR \| $3.2M \| $4.8M \| $7.1M \|
M|Resu|tx|\| ARR Growth \| 15% \| 50% \| 48% \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Employee Headcount \| 35 \| 48 \| 65 \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Employee Turnover \| 28% annually \| 12% \| 8% \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Rock Completion \| N/A \| 75% \| 88% \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Level 10 Score \| N/A \| 7.2 avg \| 8.6 avg \|
M|Resu|tx|\| ce Weekly Hours in Meetings \| 32 \| 12 \| 8 \|
M|Time|- **|** Foundation (Focus Day, VB1, VB2). Immediate reduction in ad hoc meetings.
M|Time|- **|** First quarterly sn. Scorecard revealing blind spots in cs health metrics.
M|Time|- **|** People decisions made. Core processes documented. rv growth resumed.
M|Time|- **|** EOS cascaded to all departments. Company operating as a self-managing sy.
M|Key |tx|1. The ce stepping out of day-to-day operations and into the Visionary role unlocked growth that was being bottlenecked by one person.
M|Key |tx|2. The engineering-sales conflict was not a people problem -- it was a process problem. Documenting the roadmap prioritization process resolved years of tension.
M|Key |tx|3. The weekly Scorecard caught a cs health decline that wld have resulted in major churn if not addressed early.
M|Comp|- **|** Management consulting
M|Comp|- **|** $8.5M
M|Comp|- **|** 52
M|Comp|- **|** 12 years prior
M|Comp|- **|** Managing Partner (Visionary), co (Integrator), 3 Practice Leads, Head of Business dv
M|Star|it|rv had plateaued for two years despite adding consultants
M|Star|it|Utilization rates varied wildly (50% to 95%) across practices
M|Star|it|No consistent delivery methodology; qual depended entirely on the individual consultant
M|Star|it|The Managing Partner was the only person who cld close large deals
M|Star|it|hi-potential consultants kept leaving for cr
M|EOS |**Fo|** Accountability Chart revealed that no one owned business dv as a full-time fn. The Managing Partner had been doing it as a side task. A Head of Business dv seat was created.
M|EOS |**V/|** Core Values: "Client First," "Own Your Craft," "Straight Talk," "Win Together." mk st identified the ideal client profile (mid-mk companies, $50M-$500M rv, undergoing operational transformation) and three uniques: industry-specific expertise, fixed-fee engagements, and a proprietary delivery methodology.
M|EOS |**Pr|** Three core processes were documented: "The Engagement Lifecycle" (sales to delivery to follow-up), "The Consulting Method" (the firm's proprietary delivery approach), and "The Talent Pipeline" (recruiting, onboarding, and dv).
M|EOS |**Sc|** Key metrics included weekly utilization rate, pipeline value, proposals outstanding, consultant satisfaction score, and client NPS.
M|Resu|tx|\| Metric \| Before EOS \| After 12 Months \| After 24 Months \|
M|Resu|tx|\|--------\|-----------\|-----------------\|-----------------\|
M|Resu|tx|\| rv \| $8.5M \| $10.2M \| $13.8M \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Utilization Rate \| 62% avg \| 74% avg \| 78% avg \|
M|Resu|tx|\| rv Per Consultant \| $212K \| $268K \| $310K \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Consultant Turnover \| 35% \| 18% \| 12% \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Client NPS \| 42 \| 58 \| 67 \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Rock Completion \| N/A \| 70% \| 82% \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Level 10 Score \| N/A \| 6.8 avg \| 8.3 avg \|
M|Key |tx|1. Documenting the delivery methodology ("The Consulting Method") was the single highest-impact change. It made qual consistent across all consultants and reduced the firm's dependence on individual talent.
M|Key |tx|2. Utilization rate visibility on the weekly Scorecard changed behavior immediately. Practice leads started managing capacity proactively instead of reactively.
M|Key |tx|3. Hiring a dedicated Head of Business dv freed the Managing Partner to focus on st relationships, which paradoxically increased deal flow.
M|Comp|- **|** Custom metal fabrication
M|Comp|- **|** $18M
M|Comp|- **|** 120
M|Comp|- **|** 25 years prior (second-generation family business)
M|Comp|- **|** Owner/President (Visionary), General Manager (Integrator), VP Sales, Plant Manager, Controller
M|Star|it|Profit margins had declined from 12% to 5% over five years
M|Star|it|On-time delivery rate was 71%, causing cs complaints and lost contracts
M|Star|it|The shop floor had no documented processes; veteran machinists each had their own methods
M|Star|it|The owner's son had been promoted to Plant Manager but was struggling
M|Star|it|No weekly management meetings; monthly financial reviews were the only rhythm
M|EOS |**Pe|** The People Analyzer revealed the owner's son did not have the Capacity for the Plant Manager role. After a difficult but honest conversation, he moved to a Business dv role where he excelled (he Got it, Wanted it, and had Capacity). An experienced Plant Manager was hired externally.
M|EOS |**Pr|** Five core shop floor processes were documented w/ the 20/80 rule. Each process was given a branded name and posted at the relevant workstation. Training was conducted over six weeks. qual defects dropped 40% in the first quarter after doc.
M|EOS |**Da|** A weekly Scorecard was installed tracking on-time delivery %, scrap rate, labor utilization, quoting turnaround time, and weekly rv. Numbers were displayed on a large screen on the shop floor.
M|EOS |**Tr|** Level 10 meetings were introduced for the leadership team and the shop floor supervisors. Quarterly rocks focused on operational improvements: reducing setup times, implementing a preventive maintenance schedule, and standardizing the quoting process.
M|Resu|tx|\| Metric \| Before EOS \| After 12 Months \| After 24 Months \|
M|Resu|tx|\|--------\|-----------\|-----------------\|-----------------\|
M|Resu|tx|\| rv \| $18M \| $19.5M \| $22M \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Profit Margin \| 5% \| 9% \| 13% \|
M|Resu|tx|\| On-Time Delivery \| 71% \| 88% \| 94% \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Scrap Rate \| 8% \| 4.5% \| 2.8% \|
M|Resu|tx|\| cs Complaints/Month \| 12 \| 5 \| 2 \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Employee Turnover \| 40% \| 22% \| 15% \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Rock Completion \| N/A \| 65% \| 80% \|
M|Key |tx|1. The hardest decision -- moving the owner's son out of the Plant Manager role -- was also the most impactful. Using the People Analyzer made it an objective conversation rather than a personal attack.
M|Key |tx|2. Making the Scorecard visible on the shop floor created a sense of ownership among floor workers. They started self-correcting before managers even noticed problems.
M|Key |tx|3. Manufacturing companies often resist EOS bc they think it is for "office businesses." Process doc and weekly scorecards are arguably even more impactful in production environments.
M|Comp|- **|** Digital mk agency
M|Comp|- **|** $4.2M
M|Comp|- **|** 28
M|Comp|- **|** 6 years prior
M|Comp|- **|** Founder/Creative Director (Visionary), Director of Operations (Integrator), Head of Accounts, Head of Creative, Head of Media
M|Star|it|rv was growing but profitability was near zero due to scope creep on client projects
M|Star|it|The founder was involved in every creative decision, limiting the team's output
M|Star|it|Client retention was 65% (industry average is 72%)
M|Star|it|No standardized project delivery process; every project was a "custom" engagement
M|Star|it|The team operated in constant fire-drill mode w/ no clear priorities
M|EOS |**V/|** Core Focus defined as "Make brands unforgettable" + "perf-driven creative for B2B tech companies." This immediately clarified which clients to pursue and which to stop serving. Three clients that did not fit the niche were transitioned out within two quarters.
M|EOS |**Pr|** The core delivery process ("The Impact Cycle") was documented in 12 steps from brief to launch to perf rv. Scope creep was addressed by adding a formal change request step. Every project now followed the same structure.
M|EOS |**Ro|** First quarter rocks included: define ideal client profile and up all sales materials, document The Impact Cycle, hire a Creative Director to replace the founder in day-to-day creative decisions, and im project profitability tracking.
M|EOS |**Pe|** The founder struggled to let go of creative control. An honest Visionary/Integrator conversation established boundaries: the founder wld set creative direction and handle top-tier client relationships but wld not rv every deliverable.
M|Resu|tx|\| Metric \| Before EOS \| After 12 Months \| After 24 Months \|
M|Resu|tx|\|--------\|-----------\|-----------------\|-----------------\|
M|Resu|tx|\| rv \| $4.2M \| $5.1M \| $6.8M \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Net Profit Margin \| 2% \| 12% \| 18% \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Client Retention \| 65% \| 78% \| 85% \|
M|Resu|tx|\| rv Per Employee \| $150K \| $189K \| $227K \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Scope Creep Incidents/Quarter \| 15+ \| 4 \| 1 \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Rock Completion \| N/A \| 72% \| 85% \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Founder Hours/Week on Production \| 35 \| 15 \| 5 \|
M|Key |tx|1. Narrowing the niche felt counterintuitive ("We're turning away rv!") but dramatically improved profitability and client results. Specialization commands higher prices and lower delivery costs.
M|Key |tx|2. Documenting the delivery process eliminated scope creep, which was the primary margin killer.
M|Key |tx|3. Agencies where the founder cannot delegate creative work will always have a rv ceiling. The Visionary/Integrator framework gave the founder a path to step back w/o losing influence.
M|Comp|- **|** Multi-location physical therapy practice
M|Comp|- **|** $12M
M|Comp|- **|** 85 (across 6 clinics)
M|Comp|- **|** 10 years prior
M|Comp|- **|** Founder/ce (Visionary), Practice Administrator (Integrator), Clinical Director, mk Director, fi Director
M|Star|it|Six clinics operating independently w/ inconsistent patient experiences
M|Star|it|Clinical outcomes varied significantly by location
M|Star|it|Difficulty recruiting and retaining therapists (three open positions unfilled for 6+ months)
M|Star|it|No visibility into clinic-level perf; only aggregate monthly financials
M|Star|it|The founder spent all day traveling btw clinics putting out fires
M|EOS |**Da|** A clinic-level weekly Scorecard was the first tool implemented. Each clinic tracked: new patient visits, patient visit volume, plan-of-care completion rate, patient satisfaction score, therapist utilization, and collections. Within weeks, perf differences btw clinics became visible.
M|EOS |**Pr|** The clinical delivery process ("The Recovery Path") was standardized across all six locations. Best practices from the top-performing clinic were documented and rolled out to all locations. Training was done in one quarter.
M|EOS |**Pe|** Clinic managers were assessed using GWC. Two of six managers did not have the Capacity for the expanded management role. One was moved to a senior therapist role (a better fit). One exited. Replacements were hired using the core values interview process.
M|EOS |**Tr|** Each clinic ran its own weekly Level 10 meeting. The leadership team's Level 10 reviewed company-wide Scorecard data and clinic-level issues escalated from clinic meetings.
M|Resu|tx|\| Metric \| Before EOS \| After 12 Months \| After 24 Months \|
M|Resu|tx|\|--------\|-----------\|-----------------\|-----------------\|
M|Resu|tx|\| rv \| $12M \| $14.5M \| $18M \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Clinics \| 6 \| 6 \| 8 \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Patient Satisfaction \| 4.1/5 avg \| 4.5/5 avg \| 4.7/5 avg \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Plan Completion Rate \| 62% \| 78% \| 85% \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Therapist Turnover \| 30% \| 15% \| 10% \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Open Therapist Positions \| 3 (6+ months) \| 1 (filled in 45 days) \| 0 \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Rock Completion \| N/A \| 68% \| 83% \|
M|Resu|tx|\| Founder Hours in Clinics/Week \| 40 \| 15 \| 5 \|
M|Key |tx|1. Multi-location businesses benefit enormously from EOS bc it creates consistency across locations while maintaining local autonomy through department-level Level 10 meetings.
M|Key |tx|2. The clinic-level Scorecard was transformative. Problems that had been invisible in aggregate monthly financials became obvious in weekly clinic-level data.
M|Key |tx|3. Standardizing the clinical process actually improved therapist satisfaction bc it reduced decision fatigue and gave new hires a clear playbook.
M|Comm|Acro|
M|What|tx|1. **Full leadership team commitment.** No partial adoption. Every leader attends every sn and runs Level 10 meetings in their departments.
M|What|tx|2. **Willingness to make hard people decisions.** Every company had at least one difficult personnel change in the first year. Delaying these decisions delayed results.
M|What|tx|3. **Process doc early.** Companies that documented core processes in the first two quarters saw faster improvements than those who waited.
M|What|tx|4. **Weekly Scorecard discipline.** The Scorecard catches problems early. Companies that maintained weekly discipline consistently outperformed those that slipped to biweekly or monthly reviews.
M|What|tx|5. **The Visionary steps back.** In every case, the founder/Visionary needed to delegate operational decisions to the Integrator. This was always uncomfortable and always transformative.
M|What|tx|\| sc Factor \| Successful Companies \| Failed Implementations \|
M|What|tx|\|---------------\|---------------------\|----------------------\|
M|What|tx|\| Commitment duration \| 2+ year commitment \| Quit after 6 months \|
M|What|tx|\| Level 10 consistency \| Never miss a meeting \| Cancel when "busy" \|
M|What|tx|\| People decisions \| Made within 90 days \| Avoided for quarters or years \|
M|What|tx|\| Rocks discipline \| Set SMART rocks, track weekly \| Vague rocks, tracked monthly \|
M|What|tx|\| Leadership alignment \| Openly debate, then commit \| Agree in the room, undermine outside \|
M|What|tx|\| Patience w/ results \| Expect Year 1 = foundation, Year 2 = results \| Expect immediate transformation \|
